# Flutter UI Consistency

Rules to prevent widget drift, visual patchwork, and reinventing what already exists.

## Reuse Before Create

- Before building any new widget, search the codebase for existing widgets that do something similar.
- If an existing widget does most of what you need, extend it with constructor parameters instead of creating a parallel version.
- If two widgets share the same core pattern, extract a shared widget and have both use it.
- General-purpose widgets belong in shared UI; feature-specific widgets stay inside their feature.
- Build common patterns once: audio queue rows, source pickers, empty states, loading indicators, error panels, permission prompts, and confirmation dialogs.

## No Isolated Styling

- Every new screen must visually match the rest of the app: spacing, cards, controls, typography, icons, and empty/error states.
- Before styling a new screen, compare it with the most similar existing screen and match structure first.
- Do not hardcode colors, font sizes, spacing, radii, or shadows when theme tokens can express the design.
- Prefer `ThemeData`, `ColorScheme`, text themes, and shared widgets over one-off inline styling.

## Design System as Source of Truth

- The Flutter theme and shared UI package are the authority on appearance and behavior.
- Use consistent spacing constants or theme extensions once they exist; do not invent near-duplicate values.
- Use semantic colors from `ColorScheme`; avoid one-off hex values in widgets.
- Use the app text theme; avoid arbitrary text styles unless the design system is being intentionally extended.
- Keep controls, cards, dialogs, and list rows consistent across player, library, timer, and settings screens.

## Pattern Consistency Across Pages

- Similar screens follow the same layout pattern: settings, provider setup, library, queue, and timer screens should feel like one app.
- Lists of audio files, cloud files, and queue entries should use the same row structure where possible.
- Empty states should use consistent iconography, typography, and action placement.
- Loading states should be consistent; do not mix unrelated spinner, skeleton, and shimmer patterns.
- Error states should follow one pattern with clear recovery actions.

## Shared Patterns to Extract

When you see these patterns appearing in more than one place, extract them:

- **Audio row**: title, source/provider, duration when known, and action controls.
- **Source picker**: local files and cloud providers shown with consistent affordances.
- **Confirmation dialog**: configurable title, message, confirm/cancel actions.
- **Empty state**: icon, title, description, and optional action button.
- **Screen header**: title, optional subtitle, and optional actions.
- **Async list wrapper**: loading, empty, error, and content states.

## Preventing Drift Over Time

- When modifying an existing pattern, update all instances that use that pattern.
- When adding a new screen, start from the most similar existing screen structure.
- If shared UI does not support a needed variant, extend it intentionally instead of hand-building one-off alternatives.
- If the same visual pattern exists in three or more places with slight variations, consolidate it.

## Anti-Patterns

- Building a new audio row when a shared queue/library row already exists.
- Using different card padding for the same type of content across screens.
- Creating a custom dialog for each feature instead of a shared configurable dialog.
- Hardcoding colors or typography inside widgets instead of using the theme.
- Each screen inventing its own loading, error, or empty state.
- Calling platform plugins directly from widgets while the rest of the app uses services.
